\par {\pntext\pard\plain\ltrpar \rtlch\fcs1 \af1 \ltrch\fcs0 \f1\insrsid13110295\charrsid13110295 \hich\af1\dbch\af0\loch\f1 4\tab}}\pard \ltrpar\ql \fi-360\li720\ri0\nowidctlpar\tx720\wrapdefault{\*\pn \pnlvlbody\ilvl0\ls4\pnrnot0\pndec\pnstart4\pnindent360 }
\faauto\ls4\rin0\lin720\itap0\pararsid13110295 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af1 \ltrch\fcs0 \f1\insrsid13110295\charrsid13110295 Database startup or database shutdown
\par }\pard \ltrpar\ql \li0\ri0\nowidctlpar\wrapdefault\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af1 \ltrch\fcs0 \f1\insrsid13110295\charrsid13110295 
\par 2. The different types of triggers have been categorized based on the type of event that causes the trigger to fire. There are three different types of triggers:
\par {\pntext\pard\plain\ltrpar \rtlch\fcs1 \af1 \ltrch\fcs0 \f1\insrsid13110295\charrsid13110295 \hich\af1\dbch\af0\loch\f1 1\tab}}\pard \ltrpar\ql \fi-360\li720\ri0\nowidctlpar\tx720\wrapdefault{\*\pn \pnlvlbody\ilvl0\ls5\pnrnot0\pndec\pnstart1\pnindent360 }
\faauto\ls5\rin0\lin720\itap0\pararsid13110295 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af1 \ltrch\fcs0 \f1\insrsid13110295\charrsid13110295 DML Triggers
\par {\pntext\pard\plain\ltrpar \rtlch\fcs1 \af1 \ltrch\fcs0 \f1\insrsid13110295\charrsid13110295 \hich\af1\dbch\af0\loch\f1 2\tab}}\pard \ltrpar\ql \fi-360\li720\ri0\nowidctlpar\tx720\wrapdefault{\*\pn \pnlvlbody\ilvl0\ls6\pnrnot0\pndec\pnstart2\pnindent360 }
\faauto\ls6\rin0\lin720\itap0\pararsid13110295 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af1 \ltrch\fcs0 \f1\insrsid13110295\charrsid13110295 DDL Triggers
\par {\pntext\pard\plain\ltrpar \rtlch\fcs1 \af1 \ltrch\fcs0 \f1\insrsid13110295\charrsid13110295 \hich\af1\dbch\af0\loch\f1 3\tab}}\pard \ltrpar\ql \fi-360\li720\ri0\nowidctlpar\tx720\wrapdefault{\*\pn \pnlvlbody\ilvl0\ls7\pnrnot0\pndec\pnstart3\pnindent360 }
\faauto\ls7\rin0\lin720\itap0\pararsid13110295 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af1 \ltrch\fcs0 \f1\insrsid13110295\charrsid13110295 Database Triggers
\par }\pard \ltrpar\ql \li0\ri0\sb120\sa120\nowidctlpar\wrapdefault\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af1 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f1\insrsid13110295\charrsid13110295 The DML triggers}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af1 \ltrch\fcs0 \f1\insrsid13110295\charrsid13110295 
 are fired on the execution of DML statements. The DML sta
tements on which you may write these triggers are: INSERT, UPDATE, and DELETE statements. These triggers may be executed for every row that is affected by the DML statement or once for the triggering DML statement. The time of execution of the trigger can
 be before execution of the statement or after the execution of the statement
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af1 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f1\insrsid13110295\charrsid13110295 The DDL triggers}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af1 \ltrch\fcs0 \f1\insrsid13110295\charrsid13110295 
 are fired when a CREATE, ALTER, or DROP statement is executed on any schema object. These triggers can be fired before execution of the triggering statement or af
ter execution of the triggering statement. The statements on which these triggers are fired are DDL statements, so they are named as DDL triggers. 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\ql \li0\ri0\nowidctlpar\wrapdefault\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af1 \ltrch\fcs0 \f1\insrsid13110295\charrsid13110295 3. Triggers can be defined to execute before the triggering statement executes or after the triggering state
ment has executed. This is done with the BEFORE and AFTER clauses used in the CREATE TRIGGER statement.
\par The BEFORE triggers execute before the triggering statement. Before triggers find common use when:
\par {\pntext\pard\plain\ltrpar \rtlch\fcs1 \af1 \ltrch\fcs0 \f1\insrsid13110295\charrsid13110295 \hich\af1\dbch\af0\loch\f1 1\tab}}\pard \ltrpar\ql \fi-360\li720\ri0\nowidctlpar\tx720\wrapdefault{\*\pn \pnlvlbody\ilvl0\ls8\pnrnot0\pndec\pnstart1\pnindent360 }
\faauto\ls8\rin0\lin720\itap0\pararsid13110295 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af1 \ltrch\fcs0 \f1\insrsid13110295\charrsid13110295 The triggering statement is to be restricted from execution failing the criteria specified in the trigger action. 
\par {\pntext\pard\plain\ltrpar \rtlch\fcs1 \af1 \ltrch\fcs0 \f1\insrsid13110295\charrsid13110295 \hich\af1\dbch\af0\loch\f1 2\tab}}\pard \ltrpar\ql \fi-360\li720\ri0\nowidctlpar\tx720\wrapdefault{\*\pn \pnlvlbody\ilvl0\ls9\pnrnot0\pndec\pnstart2\pnindent360 }
\faauto\ls9\rin0\lin720\itap0\pararsid13110295 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af1 \ltrch\fcs0 \f1\insrsid13110295\charrsid13110295 The triggers can also be used to derive column values for insertion or updation into a table.
\par }\pard \ltrpar\ql \li0\ri0\nowidctlpar\wrapdefault\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af1 \ltrch\fcs0 \f1\insrsid13110295\charrsid13110295 
AFTER Triggers are executed after the triggering statement has executed. For example, if you want to keep a record of the salary increment of employees at every update of employee salary, you can write a trigger that records the employee ID, the current d
ate, and the new salary in a separate table
\par 
\par 4. INSTEAD-OF triggers are used to modify views that cannot be modified by DML statements. These triggers are defined against views and never against tables. They are called INSTEAD-OF triggers because Oracle exe
cutes them instead of the DML statement firing them. The views against which INSTEAD-OF triggers are defined are not modifiable by DML statements. 
\par 
